1
00:00:00,904 --> 00:00:03,285
Our home is burning.
我が家が燃えている

2
00:00:03,310 --> 00:00:06,316
Rapid climate change is destabilizing our world.  
急速な気候変動が世界を脅かしている

3
00:00:06,341 --> 00:00:10,166
It seems our emissions will not fall quickly enough to avoid runaway warming 
排出の削減は温暖化の抑止には不十分そうで

4
00:00:10,191 --> 00:00:14,017
and we may soon hit tipping points that will lead to the collapse of ecosystems
生態系が崩壊する臨界点も近そうだし


5
00:00:14,042 --> 00:00:16,165
and our civilization.
人類の文明も危うい

6
00:00:16,761 --> 00:00:20,920
While scientists, activists and much of the younger generation urge action,
科学者、活動家、多数の若者が
行動を促すものの

7
00:00:20,945 --> 00:00:24,752
it appears most politicians are not committed to do anything meaningful
ほとんどの政治家は
意味ある活動に取り組まず

8
00:00:24,777 --> 00:00:29,349
while the fossil fuel industry still works actively against change.
化石燃料産業は依然として
変化を強く拒んでいる

9
00:00:29,374 --> 00:00:34,849
It seems humanity can't overcome its greed and obsession with short term profit and personal gain
人類は短期的・個人的な利益への欲望と執着を
克服できない

10
00:00:34,873 --> 00:00:36,318
to save itself.
保身のためだ

11
00:00:36,720 --> 00:00:40,767
And so for many the future looks grim and hopeless.
多くの人には
未来は厳しく絶望的にみえる

12
00:00:40,983 --> 00:00:44,038
Young people feel particularly anxious and depressed.
特に若者は不安で憂鬱だ

13
00:00:44,063 --> 00:00:49,063
Instead of looking ahead to a lifetime of opportunity they wonder if they will even have a future
想像するのは未来のチャンスではなく
「未来があるのか」や

14
00:00:49,103 --> 00:00:51,797
or if they should bring kids into this world.
「こんな世界に子供を産むべきか」だ

15
00:00:52,080 --> 00:00:58,198
It's an age of doom and hopelessness and giving up seems the only sensible thing to do.
今は破滅と絶望の時代であり
諦めることだけが賢明な行動に見える

16
00:00:58,484 --> 00:01:01,111
But that's not true.
だが、それは真実ではない

17
00:01:01,136 --> 00:01:06,019
You are not doomed. Humanity is not doomed.
あなたの破滅も
人類の破滅も確定していないのだ

18
00:01:13,549 --> 00:01:18,833
Despite the seriousness of the situation, for years positive trends have accumulated
深刻な状況の一方
ポジティブな動向も長期的に蓄積されており

19
00:01:18,858 --> 00:01:24,341
and there is finally some good news and a clear path towards our collective climate goals.
気候の共通目標への好材料と
明確な道筋がついに整ってきた

20
00:01:24,366 --> 00:01:27,564
Welcome to our Ted talk, please watch this video to the end
Tedトークへようこそ
最後まで視聴してください

21
00:01:27,588 --> 00:01:30,774
– check out our detailed sources afterwards to learn more.
詳細は概要欄の情報源リンクから

22
00:01:31,040 --> 00:01:34,940
Ok! Let’s start with the scariest things.
よし！まずは最も恐ろしい内容から

23
00:01:35,440 --> 00:01:37,807
Canceling the Apocalypse
【終末を拒否する】

24
00:01:38,160 --> 00:01:43,837
Some of the most widely shared stories about Climate Change are that it is an existential threat
気候変動を人類存亡の危機とする捉え方が
広く共有されている

25
00:01:43,862 --> 00:01:48,312
– the end of human civilization and maybe even our own extinction event.
文明の終焉、そして人類の絶滅まであると

26
00:01:48,337 --> 00:01:52,796
And that it is basically unavoidable now. But what does science actually say?
もはや終末は不可避とされるが
科学者の見解はどうだろう？

27
00:01:53,040 --> 00:02:00,039
As of 2022 the global average temperature has risen 1.2 degrees celsius compared to preindustrial times.
2022年現在、世界の平均気温は
産業革命以前に比べて1.2℃上昇している

28
00:02:00,240 --> 00:02:04,972
Limiting warming to 1.5 degrees was the most ambitious goal of the Paris agreement
1.5℃までに抑えるのが
パリ協定での最大目標だったが


29
00:02:04,997 --> 00:02:07,363
but we are not likely to meet it.
実現できそうにない

30
00:02:07,387 --> 00:02:11,120
Already with the warming we have today, hot places will get hotter,
すでに現時点の温暖化で
暑い地域はより暑く

31
00:02:11,120 --> 00:02:17,191
wet places wetter and the risk and strength of extreme weather events increase significantly.
湿潤な地域はより湿潤となり
異常気象のリスクと程度は有意に増加している

32
00:02:17,440 --> 00:02:21,909
Warming beyond 2 degrees makes all of these extremes more extreme,
2℃を超える温暖化は
現状をさらに悪化させる

33
00:02:21,934 --> 00:02:27,001
extreme weather events more common with more ecosystems under major pressure.
異常気象はより一般的になり
生態系への圧力も強まって

34
00:02:27,025 --> 00:02:29,207
Some will not survive.
存続できない種も出る

35
00:02:29,520 --> 00:02:33,920
At 3 degrees significant parts of earth, especially in developing countries,
3℃上昇するとかなりの地域
特に途上国で

36
00:02:33,920 --> 00:02:36,819
might become unable to feed their populations.
人口を養えなくなるかも

37
00:02:36,843 --> 00:02:39,282
Heat waves will become a major global issue.
熱波が世界の重要課題となり

38
00:02:39,440 --> 00:02:42,228
Large scale natural systems will break down.
自然界の仕組みの大枠が破壊される

39
00:02:42,252 --> 00:02:46,743
The scale and frequency of hurricanes, fires and droughts will further increase
ハリケーン、山火事、干ばつの
規模と頻度がさらに増加し

40
00:02:46,767 --> 00:02:49,112
and cause trillions in damage.
膨大な被害を招く

41
00:02:49,136 --> 00:02:52,913
Poor regions and subsistence farmers will be hit the hardest.
貧しい地域や自給自足の農家は特に深刻で

42
00:02:52,937 --> 00:02:56,469
Hundreds of millions of people will need to leave their homes.
何億人もが移住を迫られるだろう

43
00:02:56,640 --> 00:02:59,987
In the 4-8 degree range the apocalypse begins
4-8℃の上昇で終末が始まる

44
00:03:00,011 --> 00:03:03,312
– the hothouse earth, where things change so quickly,
温室状態の地球は
物事の変化が激しく

45
00:03:03,336 --> 00:03:08,637
that it may become unable to support our large human population and billions may perish,
人口を養いきれなくなって
数十億人が滅び

46
00:03:08,667 --> 00:03:11,786
leaving the rest on a hostile alien planet.
残りは見知らぬ過酷な惑星に残されるかも

47
00:03:12,118 --> 00:03:14,981
A decade ago, for lack of action and perspective,
10年前、行動と展望の欠如から

48
00:03:15,006 --> 00:03:18,817
many scientists assumed a 4+ degree world was our future
多くの科学者は
4℃以上増加する未来を想定し

49
00:03:18,842 --> 00:03:23,141
and a lot of public communication focused on exactly this future path.
多くの広報は
まさにこの未来に焦点をあてていた

50
00:03:23,520 --> 00:03:28,615
Luckily, it's much less likely that this version of the apocalypse will come to pass.
幸運にも
このような終末の可能性は低くなっている

51
00:03:29,120 --> 00:03:31,374
If current climate policies stagnate,
現在の気候政策が停滞すると

52
00:03:31,398 --> 00:03:36,349
we're likely to end up with warming 3 degrees celsius by 2100.
2100年までに3℃の温暖化で終わりそうだ

53
00:03:36,640 --> 00:03:40,833
Which is scary and tragic and far from acceptable.
これは恐ろしく、悲劇的で
受け入れられないが

54
00:03:40,857 --> 00:03:44,130
But this is actually good news – how?
いいニュースでもある
―なぜか？

55
00:03:44,154 --> 00:03:51,434
In the last decade, we have seen enough progress that most scientists now think that we have likely avoided apocalyptic climate change.
この10年で、多くの科学者が
終末的な気候変動は回避されたという立場になった

56
00:03:51,640 --> 00:03:54,252
Although substantial risk still remains,
まだ大きなリスクは残るが

57
00:03:54,276 --> 00:03:58,219
we can pretty confidently say that humanity isn't going anywhere.
人類は滅亡しないと自信を持って言える

58
00:03:58,243 --> 00:04:02,278
Civilization might have to change, but it will endure.
文明は変化を強いられるが
滅びはしない

59
00:04:02,643 --> 00:04:09,482
Which begs the question: What has changed over the last ten years and is this really good news?
ここで疑問が生じる
この10年での変化とは？それは本当に吉報なのか？

60
00:04:09,507 --> 00:04:11,342
The Invisible Shift
【見えない変化】

61
00:04:11,760 --> 00:04:13,551
You probably know this story:
次の内容はご存じかもしれない

62
00:04:13,575 --> 00:04:17,633
The last decade has been an immense failure for climate policies around the world.
「過去10年、世界の気候政策は大失敗だった」

63
00:04:17,831 --> 00:04:22,160
Instead of passing comprehensive, binding bills that would meaningfully reduce emissions
「排出削減に効果的で拘束力のある法案を通さず」

64
00:04:22,160 --> 00:04:24,339
we mostly did: nothing.
「ほぼ何もしないことを選んだ」

65
00:04:24,363 --> 00:04:27,940
A lost decade with one negative record after another.
「相次ぐネガティブ記録の
失われた10年だった」

66
00:04:27,964 --> 00:04:32,612
And this story is true and it is one reason why so many people are giving up.
この内容は正しいし
多くにとって諦める根拠だ

67
00:04:32,636 --> 00:04:34,782
But it is not the whole picture.
だが、これが全てではない

68
00:04:34,960 --> 00:04:41,120
Despite the lack of climate policies and ongoing lobbying and misinformation campaigns from the fossil fuel industries,
気候政策の欠如や
化石燃料産業によるロビー活動と情報攪乱の一方

69
00:04:41,120 --> 00:04:43,266
there was a lot of progress.
多くの進展もあったのだ

70
00:04:43,290 --> 00:04:47,359
Let us go back 20 years to see why today is so different:
現状の変化を見るため
20年前に戻ろう

71
00:04:48,000 --> 00:04:50,603
Between 2000 and 2010,
2000年-2010年

72
00:04:50,627 --> 00:04:53,872
greenhouse gas emissions had grown by 24%,
温室効果ガスの排出量は24％増加し

73
00:04:53,897 --> 00:04:57,233
three times as much as the increase in the previous decade.
過去10年の増加量の3倍だった

74
00:04:57,257 --> 00:05:01,282
Subsidies for fossil fuels aimed at promoting economic growth,
経済成長のための
化石燃料への補助金が

75
00:05:01,306 --> 00:05:04,138
caused a colossal increase in their consumption.
消費量を激増させたのだ

76
00:05:04,320 --> 00:05:08,800
For emerging countries like China and India coal was the cheapest fuel for growth
中国やインド等の新興国には
石炭は最も安価な燃料で

77
00:05:08,800 --> 00:05:12,375
while rich countries showed little interest in changing their ways.
豊かな国々も変わろうとしなかった

78
00:05:12,400 --> 00:05:15,721
In 2010, many people expected these trends to continue.
2010年、この傾向が続くと多数が思った

79
00:05:15,745 --> 00:05:20,004
Instead of decreasing fossil fuel use its consumption would rise.
化石燃料の利用は低下でなく増加するのだと

80
00:05:20,199 --> 00:05:23,350
The next decade turned out to be very different though.
だが次の10年は全く違った

81
00:05:23,839 --> 00:05:30,128
First of all, coal burning in emerging countries like India
has been slowed down or leveled off, like in China.
まず、インドなど新興国での石炭利用は
中国のように安定または低下しており

82
00:05:30,152 --> 00:05:33,805
And it has plummeted in rich countries like the UK and US.
英米のような富裕国では急落している

83
00:05:34,119 --> 00:05:41,354
Since 2015 three-quarters of planned coal plants have been canceled
and 44 countries have committed to stop building them.
2015年以降、石炭発電所の計画の3/4が中止となり
44ヵ国が新設を見送った

84
00:05:41,544 --> 00:05:44,240
Ten years ago that would have seemed like wishful thinking,
10年前なら楽観論だが

85
00:05:44,240 --> 00:05:47,897
but today we can say with confidence: Coal is dying.
今は断言できる：石炭は死につつある

86
00:05:47,921 --> 00:05:50,240
It is just not competitive anymore.
もはや競争力がない

87
00:05:50,240 --> 00:05:53,197
Because technologies we thought would remain expensive
当面は高価だろうという技術が

88
00:05:53,221 --> 00:05:55,712
matured rapidly instead.
急速に成熟したからだ

89
00:05:55,990 --> 00:05:59,663
Renewable electricity has shown explosive progress.
再生可能エネルギーは爆発的に進歩した

90
00:05:59,687 --> 00:06:03,142
In a mere decade wind energy got three times cheaper.
たった10年で風力発電は3倍安く

91
00:06:03,280 --> 00:06:06,356
Solar electricity is now ten times cheaper!
太陽光は10倍安くなっている

92
00:06:06,519 --> 00:06:09,928
Cheaper than coal or any other fossil-fuel burning power plant,
これは石炭や他の化石燃料の発電より安い

93
00:06:09,952 --> 00:06:15,115
despite the massive subsidies and global infrastructure propping up fossil fuels.
化石燃料には世界的なインフラと
巨額の補助金があるのにだ

94
00:06:15,440 --> 00:06:22,428
25 times more solar and nearly 5 times more wind electricity is produced today compared with ten years ago,
10年前と比べ、太陽光発電は25倍
風力発電は5倍近く行われているが

95
00:06:22,453 --> 00:06:24,911
which is of course not nearly enough.
もちろん全く十分でない

96
00:06:24,935 --> 00:06:29,163
One of the biggest obstacles is the variability of their power output.
最大の障害の一つは
その出力のバラつきだ

97
00:06:29,188 --> 00:06:34,894
Renewables need a lot of energy storage to be a reliable power source,
like expensive batteries.
再生可能エネルギーの信頼獲得には
高級バッテリーのような貯蔵先が多数必要だ

98
00:06:34,918 --> 00:06:40,320
Amazingly battery prices have decreased by 97% in the past 30 years,
驚くべきことに
バッテリーの価格低下は過去30年で97％

99
00:06:40,320 --> 00:06:42,663
60% in the last decade alone
10年だけでも60％で

100
00:06:42,688 --> 00:06:46,615
– which will serve all kinds of green technology like electric cars.
電気自動車など
全てのグリーンテクノロジーに有用だ

101
00:06:46,875 --> 00:06:51,015
You might say, well that's great but didn't Kurzgesagt's last climate video
素晴らしいことだが
Kurzgesagtの前回の気候動画の主張は

102
00:06:51,040 --> 00:06:57,978
say that while wind and solar are nice, we need nothing less than a fundamental transition of our global industrial system?
「風力や太陽光は重要だが
産業システムの根本的な転換が最重要」では？

103
00:06:58,002 --> 00:07:02,160
Yes but luckily the shift goes beyond just the energy sector.
その通りだが
幸運にも躍進はエネルギー部門だけではない

104
00:07:02,160 --> 00:07:07,274
Throughout the economy people are working on improving current technology to lower emissions.
経済全体で
人々は排出削減への技術改善に取り組んだ

105
00:07:07,680 --> 00:07:13,790
We're rapidly replacing old incandescent light bulbs
with LEDs that are ten times more efficient.
古い白熱電球を、効率10倍のLEDへと
急速に置き換えている

106
00:07:13,920 --> 00:07:19,224
In 2020 about 7 out of 10 new cars in Norway were electric or hybrid
2020年、新車の10台中7台が
電気自動車かハイブリッド車だった

107
00:07:19,264 --> 00:07:22,611
– In 2021 it was already 8 out of 10.
2021年には10台中8台だ

108
00:07:22,889 --> 00:07:29,840
And the list goes on, from electric heating and better insulation to ships traveling at half speed to save fuel.
改善リストは、電気暖房や断熱材の改善から
速度を半分にして燃料を節約する船まで続く

109
00:07:29,840 --> 00:07:33,295
Wherever you look you find scientists, engineers and entrepreneurs
どこにでも科学者、技術者、起業家がいて

110
00:07:33,320 --> 00:07:36,238
trying to solve some aspect of climate change.
気候変動の関係に取り組んでいる

111
00:07:36,434 --> 00:07:40,542
Enormous amounts of human ingenuity are being brought to bear on this problem
急速な気候変動の抑制を
人々が重視するほどに

112
00:07:40,567 --> 00:07:45,244
with more and more people deciding to prioritize preventing rapid climate change.
人類の膨大な創意工夫が
問題解決に活用される

113
00:07:45,771 --> 00:07:50,398
Solutions for low-carbon production of cement, electronics and steel,
セメント、電子機器、鉄鋼の
低炭素での生産方法や

114
00:07:50,423 --> 00:07:54,678
and innovations like artificial meat and carbon capture are in the works.
人工肉や炭素回収等の技術革新が進行中だ

115
00:07:54,702 --> 00:07:59,738
The more of these technologies we deploy; the cheaper new and better technology gets.
これら技術を導入するほど
優れた新技術の価格が下がる

116
00:08:00,068 --> 00:08:03,337
The cheaper they get, the more people use them. And so on.
安価なら需要も増え、という具合だ

117
00:08:03,496 --> 00:08:05,200
We can see the impact already:
影響は確認済みで

118
00:08:05,200 --> 00:08:09,766
The domestic CO2 output of rich countries is falling without a major recession.
大きな不況もなく
富裕国のCO2排出量は減少している

119
00:08:10,000 --> 00:08:14,497
Since the 2000, the EU as a whole shows a 21% decrease,
2000年以降、EU全体では21％

120
00:08:14,521 --> 00:08:19,674
Italy 28%, the UK 35%, Denmark 43%.
イタリアで28％、イギリスで35％
デンマークで43％も減少している

121
00:08:19,880 --> 00:08:25,099
But the best news may be that emissions are no longer necessarily coupled with economic growth.
更に良い知らせは排出が
成長と連動しなくなったことにある

122
00:08:25,377 --> 00:08:28,386
In the past this was an inconvenient truth
かつて、豊かになるためには

123
00:08:28,410 --> 00:08:30,633
– to get richer, you had to emit more.
排出量を増やす必要があった

124
00:08:30,658 --> 00:08:36,105
Which led to fierce arguments between developing and developed countries about the fairness of reducing emissions
そのため国の間で激論が交わされた
排出量低減は貧困の維持を意味し

125
00:08:36,130 --> 00:08:38,236
while their populations were still poor.
公平性に問題があったが

126
00:08:38,260 --> 00:08:43,584
But in the last decade we have seen that it IS possible to increase prosperity without increasing emissions.
この10年で経済成長は
排出を増やさなくても可能だとわかった

127
00:08:43,609 --> 00:08:49,602
missions in the Czech Republic dropped 13% while their GDP grew by 27%!
チェコ共和国は排出量を13％低減したにもかかわらず
GDPは27％成長した

128
00:08:49,626 --> 00:08:56,426
France reduced their CO2 emissions by 14% while increasing GDP by 15%!
フランスは排出量を14％低減した一方
GDPは15％増加し

129
00:08:56,619 --> 00:09:00,826
Romania saw an 8% decrease and 35% growth!
ルーマニアも8％減少し、35％成長した

130
00:09:01,122 --> 00:09:04,163
And even the largest economy on earth - the USA
そして最大の経済大国アメリカでさえ

131
00:09:04,202 --> 00:09:09,350
- decreased emissions by 4% while growing their GDP by 26%!
排出量は4％減少した一方GDPは26％成長している

132
00:09:09,760 --> 00:09:12,029
Some of you may call this a numbers trick.
これらを数字上のトリックと言う者もいるだろう

133
00:09:12,053 --> 00:09:15,280
That rich countries are just exporting emissions to poorer nations
豊かな国は製造業などの排出量の多い汚れ仕事を

134
00:09:15,305 --> 00:09:18,751
by moving the dirty parts of their economies like manufacturing.
貧しい国に押し付けているに過ぎないと

135
00:09:18,776 --> 00:09:21,423
But even when we account for all of our imported goods,
しかしたとえすべての輸入品を考慮に入れたとしても

136
00:09:21,447 --> 00:09:23,881
the numbers still look positive!
この数字は依然プラスとなる

137
00:09:23,905 --> 00:09:27,936
It's no longer a matter of having to choose between prosperity and the climate
もはや一昔前の、繁栄と気候のどちらを取るか

138
00:09:27,960 --> 00:09:29,855
as it seemed to be a decade ago.
というような問題ではないのだ

139
00:09:30,093 --> 00:09:32,336
Developing countries will profit from that
途上国は後追いのおかげで

140
00:09:32,360 --> 00:09:36,643
because as rich countries pay for the expensive development of green technologies,
富裕国が開発費用を負担した技術を

141
00:09:36,667 --> 00:09:38,686
they can adopt them more cheaply.
格安で導入できる

142
00:09:38,710 --> 00:09:42,730
They can skip most of the high emission phase that today's rich countries went through.
彼らは最も排出量の高かった工程をスキップできるのだ

143
00:09:42,960 --> 00:09:47,938
We are at the point where not decarbonizing is a bad business decision.
我々は脱炭素しないという決定が
非合理であるという地点にいる

144
00:09:48,480 --> 00:09:52,284
And we haven't even really talked about solutions like carbon capture.
炭素回収のような解決策については
まだ十分に議論されていない

145
00:09:52,560 --> 00:09:55,016
In 2000 it didn't really exist.
2000年時点では存在すらしていなかったが

146
00:09:55,041 --> 00:09:57,953
In 2022 that technology does exist
2022年現在、これらの技術は存在し

147
00:09:57,978 --> 00:10:02,454
and costs around $600 to remove one ton of CO2 from the atmosphere.
1トンCO2を除去するのに600ドルかかっている

148
00:10:02,734 --> 00:10:06,511
As investment pours in and the technology matures and begins to scale,
投資が行われ技術が成熟して
規模が拡大すると

149
00:10:06,536 --> 00:10:10,248
it is likely that these costs will plummet over the next few decades.
コストは今後急落すると思われる

150
00:10:10,273 --> 00:10:12,891
So everything's fine then?
つまり、何も問題はないのだろうか？

151
00:10:12,915 --> 00:10:14,590
Well let us not get carried away here
まあ、そうは問屋が卸さない

152
00:10:14,614 --> 00:10:17,932
- all of these processes are great but not nearly fast enough.
これらの技術は素晴らしいが速度が足りない

153
00:10:17,957 --> 00:10:22,829
We are still doing way too little and technology will not magically solve everything.
我々の行動はまだ少なく
技術も魔法のようにはいかない

154
00:10:22,854 --> 00:10:25,693
We need to use fewer resources and use them longer,
我々は資源を節約し長く使い

155
00:10:25,717 --> 00:10:31,501
design consumer goods that are repairable and durable and decrease our energy requirements.
修理可能で長持ちする製品を作り
使用エネルギーを削減する必要がある

156
00:10:31,525 --> 00:10:35,535
We need much better infrastructure, agriculture and cities.
またインフラ、農業、街づくりを
改善する必要がある

157
00:10:35,559 --> 00:10:40,092
It will still be hard work, especially to get the right policies passed and enacted.
特に適切な政策を成立させるのは
相変わらず難題だが

158
00:10:40,117 --> 00:10:45,905
But for the first time ever, there are a few trendlines pointing solidly in the right direction.
いつくかの傾向は
正しい方向を示し始めたのだ

159
00:10:45,930 --> 00:10:51,013
And now imagine – If all of this was achieved without proper financial and political support
想像したい
もしこれらが適切な財政及び政治的支援なく

160
00:10:51,037 --> 00:10:53,452
and despite fossil fuel lobbying
化石燃料のロビー活動にも関わらず達成されたとしたら

161
00:10:53,477 --> 00:10:59,832
– just think what humanity can do when climate change finally gets the political attention and funding it needs.
考えてほしい、気候変動が政治的注目と
資金を得たとき人類に何ができるかを

162
00:10:59,856 --> 00:11:02,448
So is it ok to feel hopeful again?
うん、やっぱり希望が見えてきそう？

163
00:11:02,448 --> 00:11:04,798
The situation is still dire and serious,
状況はいまだ深刻だ

164
00:11:04,822 --> 00:11:08,310
so what is the point of focusing on this side of the story?
じゃあ、この側面に注目する理由は？

165
00:11:08,856 --> 00:11:11,574
The Trap of Hopelessness
【絶望という罠】

166
00:11:12,196 --> 00:11:16,352
Climate change can feel overwhelming and make your future seem bleak.
気候変動に圧倒され
未来は暗いと思うことがある

167
00:11:16,595 --> 00:11:23,232
The sadness and hopelessness that many people feel is real and very destructive because it causes apathy.
悲しみや絶望感は現実であり
破壊を見過ごす無関心へと繋がりがちだ

168
00:11:23,257 --> 00:11:26,234
Apathy that is only serving the fossil fuel industry
無関心とは化石燃料産業を救うものであり

169
00:11:26,259 --> 00:11:29,157
that is still delaying change however it can.
彼らはできる限り変化を遅らせようとしている

170
00:11:29,198 --> 00:11:32,766
In a sense they have weaponized hopelessness.
ある意味、彼らは絶望を武器としているのだ

171
00:11:33,033 --> 00:11:37,529
We are now in phase 4 in the public debate about rapid climate change action:
我々は急速な気候変動に対して第4段階目にいる

172
00:11:37,870 --> 00:11:41,134
Phase 1 was: Climate Change is not real.
第1段階は
「気候変動は事実ではない」

173
00:11:41,284 --> 00:11:45,711
Phase 2 was: Climate Change is real but not caused by humans.
第2段階は「気候変動は事実だ
しかし人類が原因ではない」

174
00:11:45,742 --> 00:11:50,440
Phase 3 was: Climate Change may be caused by humans but it's not that bad.
第3段階は「気候変動は人類が原因だ
しかしさほど悪いことではない」

175
00:11:50,465 --> 00:11:54,214
Phase 4 is: Climate Change is no longer avoidable.
第4段階は
「気候変動は避けられない」

176
00:11:54,238 --> 00:11:57,288
We are doomed and it doesn't matter what we do.
「人類がなにをしようともう手遅れだ」

177
00:11:57,684 --> 00:12:02,167
If we want the world to change, we first need to believe that change is possible.
もし世界を変えたいと望むなら
まず変化が可能だと信じる必要があり

178
00:12:02,191 --> 00:12:05,092
And we have an abundance of evidence that it is.
実際それが可能であると示す証拠も持っている

179
00:12:05,229 --> 00:12:08,136
Changes to our industrial system are gaining momentum,
変化に対し、産業は勢いを増し

180
00:12:08,161 --> 00:12:13,646
technology gets better and cheaper, climate change has become a key issue in most free elections.
技術は安く高度になり
気候変動は多くの自由選挙で重要な争点となってきた

181
00:12:13,671 --> 00:12:16,709
As more and more younger people move into influential positions,
多くの若者達が影響力をもつにつれ

182
00:12:16,733 --> 00:12:20,118
they prioritize climate change and work on new solutions.
気候変動は優先され
新しい解決策への取り組みも増えている

183
00:12:20,339 --> 00:12:23,807
In 2022 most governments not only acknowledge it
2022年では多くの政府が

184
00:12:23,831 --> 00:12:29,160
but set their own net zero goals – in democratic and autocratic countries.
ネットゼロを目標としている
民主的あるいは専制的政治体系にかかわらずだ

185
00:12:29,484 --> 00:12:34,424
The results of years of fighting a steep uphill battle are now clearly visible.
険しい道程を長年戦い続けてきた成果が
今はっきりと現れているのだ

186
00:12:34,455 --> 00:12:40,470
The pressure needs to keep increasing, to make sure that the promises made today are actually kept!
今日の約束が本当に守られるよう
圧力をかけ続ける必要がある

187
00:12:41,137 --> 00:12:46,770
Climate doomerism is the equivalent of giving up even though you can still prevent not just the worst case
気候破滅主義は諦めることに等しい
まだ我々が最悪のケースを防げるばかりか

188
00:12:46,795 --> 00:12:51,096
but also mitigate most of the bad things, make changes in time to adapt better
多くの悪影響を和らげ
変化を間に合わせ

189
00:12:51,120 --> 00:12:53,624
and prevent the poorest from suffering.
まだ貧困層の苦痛すら防げるのに

190
00:12:53,649 --> 00:12:57,970
That is why hopelessness and apathy are so dangerous.
これこそ絶望と無関心が危険な理由だ

191
00:12:58,128 --> 00:13:01,759
If the last, in many ways wasted decade, has shown anything,
もしこの10年間が無駄だったと感じられたとしても

192
00:13:01,783 --> 00:13:04,547
then it's that progress is being made
それは進歩があったということであり

193
00:13:04,571 --> 00:13:09,484
and that dire scenarios are just predictions – not our sealed fate.
悲惨なシナリオは単なる予想であって
未来が確定したわけではないのだ

194
00:13:09,508 --> 00:13:15,412
As of 2022, based on current global policies, we will end up in a 3 degrees world.
2022年現在、世界的な政策に基づくと
我々は3℃の世界に行き着くが

195
00:13:15,906 --> 00:13:19,182
Now it is our job to yet again prove the predictions wrong
この予想も誤りだったと証明する必要がある

196
00:13:19,206 --> 00:13:21,843
– despite how serious and urgent things are.
いかに事態が深刻で緊急であったとしても

197
00:13:21,867 --> 00:13:26,870
To turn that 3 degrees into a 2 degrees and then see where we can go from there.
3℃を2℃にし、さらに
未来を希求する必要がある

198
00:13:26,894 --> 00:13:28,875
For that we need hope.
そのためにも、希望が必要だ

199
00:13:29,280 --> 00:13:32,888
And we hope we gave you that today, at least a little.
そして今回、我々が少しでも
それを視聴者に与えられたらと願う

200
00:13:32,912 --> 00:13:36,837
That you feel that things are serious but also that you have a future.
事態は深刻だが
未来もあるのだと感じてもらえたなら

201
00:13:37,019 --> 00:13:40,378
That you can have kids without dooming them or the world.
子供を持つことができ
その未来も世界も破滅する宿命にないのだと

202
00:13:40,557 --> 00:13:43,149
That taking action today is worth it.
今、行動を起こすことはそれだけの価値がある

203
00:13:43,174 --> 00:13:49,032
And that despite powerful industries doing everything to delay it, society is changing.
強力な産業界がいかなる遅滞工作に勤しもうと
社会は変わりつつある

204
00:13:49,206 --> 00:13:52,525
If you need a more concrete roadmap of what you can do personally
もし自分に何ができるのか
具体的なロードマップを知りたければ

205
